There seems to be a strong agreement on that fiscal capacities are a prerequisite for state-building. Unfortunately, there have not been many attempts to explain when fiscal capacities in the developing world emerged.\footnote{\citet[5]{DiJohn2006}.} With a few exceptions, most efforts have been devoted to understanding the relationship between the politics of taxation and state development only in a limited number of European cases. In a recently edited volume, \citet[3]{Monson2015} explain that the ``New Fiscal History has furnished a valuable set of concepts and questions but so far its scope has been limited to post-classical Europe.''\footnote{Some important exceptions are \citet{Yun-Casalilla:2015zm} and \citet[]{Monson2015} who study a number of premodern Latin American states.} In fact, the bulk of the research done on Latin America has mostly focused on recent tax reforms.\footnote{For instance, \citet[]{Fairfield2013} studies different strategies policymakers pursue to tax elites starting in 1990, \citet[]{Mahon2004} and \citet{Focanti2013} study the causes of tax reform in Latin America starting in the 1980s and 1990, respectively. Similarly, \citet[]{Ross2004} studies the relationship between taxation and representation between 1971 and 1997, whereas \citet{Sokoloff2007a} study the evolution of tax institutions comparing the U.S. with Latin America. See also \citet{Sanchez2011} and \citet{Bergman2003}.} However, the origins, and moreover, the timing of fiscal expansion in Latin America, remains relatively unclear. Additionally, since wars in Latin America have been rare,\footnote{\citet{Centeno:2002qf}.} it is difficult to extend models developed to understanding the medieval European case based on external threats.\footnote{\citet{Tilly:1992rr}.} Importantly, domestic explanations, such as the role of sectoral conflicts within a context of economic structural transformation, taxation and state-building, has been overlooked.\footnote{A few exceptions are \citet[7-8]{Gallo:1991kx}, \citet{Beramendi2016} and \citet[8]{Saylor:2014aa} who consider elite conflicts to study state-making and fiscal development in the developing world. \citet[]{Wheeler2011} studies how inter-elite cooperation and agreements positively impacted state-making in Europe.} \citet[2]{Schneider:2012rr} explains that even when we have gained considerable knowledge of fiscal expansion in the European cases, the study of developing countries is lacking especially in the presence of `new leading sectors.' Building on the fiscal sociology approach I develop an argument centered on the development of the modern fiscal apparatus in Latin America explaining that it was product of sectoral conflicts and compromises between the industrial and agricultural political elites. The paper presents several panel-data analyses covering almost 100 years of sectoral outputs for a number of Latin American countries and the Chilean case to illustrate the causal mechanisms at work. Particularly, I find that the emergence of the industrial sector \emph{accelerated} the implementation of the income tax while the expansion of the agricultural sector \emph{retarded} or even \emph{precluded} fiscal development. These findings go in line with \citet{Beramendi2016}, particularly, in that as long as agriculture is the leading economic sector, the fiscal apparatus is less likely to emerge.

