I argue that the early implementation of the income tax in Latin America was product of an inter-sectoral conflict that took place around in the early 1900's between the agricultural and industrial sectors. Initially, Latin American political institutions and social norms largely inherited from the colonial period were designed to serve the interests of the landowning elites. However, the economic structural transformation characterized by ``a secular decline of agriculture and substantial expansion of manufacturing''\footnote{\citet[567]{Johnston1961}.} imposed tight constraints on the way politics was run by the incumbent agricultural political elites. Given the initial advantage of the landed elites, the emergence of the industrial sector meant the reduction of inter-sectoral inequality. Lower levels of inter-sectoral inequality posed credible political, economic and military threats to the agricultural incumbents, increasing the opportunity costs of conflict, generating pressures for inter-elite compromises.  Analytically, the emergence of the industrial sector not only altered the structure of the economy but also the inter-sectoral balance of \emph{political} power, triggering a series of inter-sectoral compromises. Here I identify one such compromise, the implementation of the income tax law. In this paper I leverage a number of Cox regressions using comparative data on a number of Latin American countries to suggest that a rapid expanding industrial sector accelerated the implementation of the income tax. To explore the causal mechanisms at work more deeply, I present the Chilean case to show that the industrial elites accepted to be income taxed by agriculturalist incumbents in exchange of opening access to state politics and the delivery of public goods at the local level. 



%
\emph{When} countries implement the income tax is an analytically important quantity of interest. For instance, Chile imposed the income tax law very early in 1924, and the Chilean \emph{Servicio de Impuestos Internos} is among the finest tax institutions in Latin America. However, Guatemala imposed the income tax law very late in 1963. By 1967, the national income tax office employed only 194 people, with only 9 of them with a college degree.\footnote{\citet[5]{DiJohn2006}.} From a theoretical perspective, I explain this variation focusing on how implementing the income tax was an important critical juncture for state-making. As explained later, fiscal sociologists contend that an important feature of income taxation are its positive externalities for state-capacities. I focus on how differences in levels of sectoral contestation delayed or accelerated the timing of the implementation of the tax.\footnote{Some scholars situate the relevant state-building critical juncture at the end of the colonial period, before the class compromises I identify in this paper. For example \citet{Kurtz2009,Kurtz:2013aa} explains that the first critical juncture corresponded to the post independence political economy, stressing whether local rural elites recruited their workers through servile means. In turn, \citet[6]{Soifer2015a} argues that the critical tipping point was whether  ``local administrators were outsiders in the communities in which they served.'' Both critical junctures happened before 1900. While the process of state-building started before 1900, the paper identifies the income tax as an important additional building block in that process.} Particularly, I explain how early implementers were able to crystallize in an endogenous way a series of reforms and inter-elite compromises that fostered state building in the long run. Late implementers, however, due to their lower levels of sectoral contestation, reproduced the legacy of post-colonial institutions. In these cases, the conflict was too low to trigger a critical juncture, reinforcing the institutional order inherited during colonial times. Even when the tax was (lately) implemented, the process of implementing it did not reflect the domestic sectoral dynamics, but other forces. For instance, the income tax in Chile was implemented under circumstances of political contestation, replacing the old institutional order, producing not only long-term economic growth,\footnote{\citet{Bahamonde:2017aa}.} but also state-capacities overtime.\footnote{\citet{Bahamonde:2017ac}.} However, while Guatemala did eventually implement the tax, the process did not reflect the foundational sectoral cleavage, truncating the development of state institutions in the long run. In fact, the law responded to exogenous forces. Particularly, the law was implemented by the US-backed dictator Colonel Enrique Peralta Azurdia, not necessarily reflecting the inter-sectoral domestic dynamics. In these kinds of scenarios, landowners were never challenged and there were less pressures to centralize the state, making further institutional investments less likely. These results go in line with \citet[7]{Beramendi2016} in that `so long as agricultural elites are the dominant political power-holders in society, then fiscal capacity should remain relatively small, because such elites will prefer \emph{not} to invest in greater fiscal capacity.'\footnote{Emphasis in original. See also for a similar approach \citet{Ansell:2014ty} and \citet{Collier:2002db}.} Consequently, the tax was not (only) important because of the new revenue it collected, but because its implementation required a series of sectoral compromises, triggering a series of other institutional investments, such as the implementation of checks-and-balances (to monitor tax spending) and the development of skilled bureaucracies. 




% How Taxation Relates to State Building: Fiscal Sociology
\section{Taxation and State Formation\label{fiscal:sociology}}


% fiscal sociology: state made tax, the tax made the state.
The paper follows the Schumpeterian view, particularly, seeing ``taxation in terms of group conflicts [and] class interests.''\footnote{\citet[14]{Monson2015}. For an excellent overview of both classic and new fiscal sociology refer to \citet[Ch. 1]{Martin2009a}.} And in turn, it examines the well-established link between direct taxation and state-making. Thus, the crux of the argument is that sectoral conflicts triggered state development by fostering fiscal expansion. This line of argumentation goes in line with \citet[99]{Musgrave1992} who explains that since taxation (especially on incomes) requires such a high degree of state penetration, public finances offer the key for a theory of state development. This link is endogenous. \citet[35]{Schneider:2012rr} explains that `[p]ublic finances are causal and symptomatic.'\footnote{He continues: ``Revenues are necessary to build states; the act of gathering revenues structures societies; productive societies and capable states generate revenues.''} Consequently, this argument goes against the conventional wisdom. Unlike \citet[206]{Besley2013a}, I find that conflict is not exogenous but rather endogenous to the implementation of the tax itself.



% INDIRECT and DIRECT
Indirect taxes do not need to develop a strong fiscal apparatus.\footnote{However, see \citet[56]{Brewer1990}. The English state made extensive use of its navy to prevent smuggling and enforce the excise, an indirect tax. The excise employed an important number of state agents and helped to develop skilled state bureaucracies and an efficient fiscal system.} According to \citet[53]{Best1976}, ``indirect taxes are but substitutes for direct taxes,''\footnote{However, under certain circumstances, indirect taxes are more efficient. \citet[291]{Kiser1994} explains that when the levels of tax variability are high, direct taxation can actually have negative effects, especially when overtaxation is a possibility.} and hence they are typically administered by weak states.\footnote{This view is also supported by \citet[14]{Moore2004}.} Since indirect taxes are easier to levy,\footnote{\citet[46]{Krasner:1985lq} explains that ``tariffs and export taxes are easier to obtain than direct taxes, which require high levels of bureaucratic skill and voluntary compliance.''} this kind of revenue is generally considered ``unearned income''\footnote{\citet[304]{Moore2004a}.} or ``easy-to-collect source of revenues.''\footnote{\citet[10]{Coatsworth2002}.} Given the relatively lower costs states have to incur to collect them, indirect taxes have a very low impact on state-building. In fact, when early Latin American states depended heavily on international trade taxes, the state apparatus tended to be less developed.\footnote{\citet[177]{Campbell1993}.} Since customs administrations in the region have always been concentrated in a few critical locations, especially ports, tariffs and customs duties did not require an elaborate fiscal structure.\footnote{\citet[132]{Bertola2012}.} Direct taxes are more likely to produce long-lasting positive externalities on state-building. Since direct taxation involves a compulsory transfer from private hands to the government sector for public purposes,\footnote{\emph{Cfr.} Raja Chellia, ``Trends in Taxation in Developing Countries,'' in \citet[282]{Migdal:1988nr}.} it is harder to collect,\footnote{\citet[62]{Kurtz:2013aa}.} requiring stronger domestic alliances to sustain these kinds of policies. From a historical standpoint, its introduction ``was one of the major events in fiscal history that contributed to the growth in \emph{government} observed during the past 150 years.''\footnote{\citet[171]{Aidt2009a}. Emphasis is mine.} Since taxing incomes involves transforming private income into public property,\footnote{\citet[98]{Musgrave1992}.} this form of taxation demands the endogenous development of both stronger state institutions and efficient monitoring and enforcement technologies.\footnote{\citet[99]{Lieberman2002a}.} 


% conflict
\citet[1085]{Hechter1980a} explain that ``state formation will be most likely to the degree that powerful individual actors form two groups on the basis of \emph{divergent} economic and political interests.''\footnote{Emphasis is mine.} Here I contend that since state centralization affects landowners and industrialists in different ways, both sectors have different preferences towards taxation and state centralization.\footnote{See \citet[289]{Acemoglu:1996rm} and \citet[50]{Best1976}.} On the one hand, land fixity increases the risk premium of the landed elite's main asset,\footnote{\citet[512]{Robinson2006a}.} so they systematically resist taxation. In turn, as capital can be reinvested in nontaxable sectors,\footnote{\citet[]{Hirschman:1970bl}. See Ronald Rogowski in \citet[ch. 4]{Drake:1998pi}. However, see \citet[15]{Bates1985}.} industrialists' preferences toward taxation are more elastic. These cross-sectoral tensions are most likely to resolve in favor of inter-sectoral cooperation - particularly, implementing the income tax law - when income inequality among the elites is low.\footnote{\citet[157]{Tani1966} explains that the absence of ``wealth groups'' makes passing an income tax law easier.} In Latin America, the post-colonial institutional and economical order was designed to give an unfair advantage to the agricultural sector.\footnote{\citet{Bahamonde:2017aa}.} However, the emergence of a strong industrial class put heavier pressures for higher levels of state centralization and investment in public goods at the local level.\footnote{\citet{Bahamonde:2017ac}.} In fact, not only sustained industrial expansion depended on the implementation of the income tax. \citet[18]{Beramendi2016} explain that as industrialists depended more on infrastructure implemented at the local level such as roads, railroads and bridges, they ``[\emph{preferred}] to shoulder a higher tax burden through progressive direct taxation.'' But also, lower levels of inter-elite economic inequality implied similar degrees of military capabilities.\footnote{\citet{Boix:2015aa}.} Under these circumstances, war was most likely to exhaust all existent assets without producing positive outcomes for either sector,\footnote{Richard Salvucci in \citet[48]{Uribe-Uran:2001aa}.} putting heavier pressures to reach agreements instead of engaging in armed conflicts. 





% income tax --> positive externalities of income taxation
The tax was not only important because of the new revenue it collected, however. While Humud (1969, p. 154) explains that the income tax generated considerable resources for the Chilean treasury,\footnote{\citet[451-452]{Bowman1982}.} the tax was also important for state-making. Not only observing individual economies, but transforming them into public property fostered state expansion.\footnote{\citet[298]{Moore2004a}.} This argument goes in line with \citet{Besley2013a} who explain that \emph{implementing} the income tax law has been ``associated with investments in public administrative structures that support tax collection'' in a number of countries, including Chile. Similarly, \citet[3]{Dincecco2015a} find ``a positive and significant relationship between the \emph{introduction} of the income tax and (1) per capita total expenditures, (2) per capita education expenditures, and (3) per capita health expenditures.''\footnote{Emphasis is mine.} I contend that the knowledge and expertise the state accumulated were transfered to other state institutions via spillovers, augmenting the overall levels of \emph{stateness}. For instance, it was necessary to send official emissaries to check on accounting books of the refinery in the north, the winery in the central valley and the \emph{hacienda} in the south. Eventually, these delegations became more complex, increasing the density of state presence in the territory. For instance, \citet{Strayer:2005uq} explains how official state delegations traveled the territory dispensing judicial decisions, fostering state centralization. In the same line, \citet{Dincecco2015} explains that states became effective organisms upon centralizing a system of direct taxation and implementing some kind of checks-and-balances system. As explained in \autoref{unpacking} the Chilean case met these two conditions. Analytically, the \emph{effectiveness} of income taxation on fiscal \emph{capacities} increased due to the nature of the implementation of the income tax. \citet[566]{Aghion2004} explain how optimal institutional choices result from political settings where all involved actors ``had a voice in the choice of institutions,'' essentially contributing to an equilibrium of quasi-voluntary compliance.\footnote{\citet{Levi:1989lq}.} In line with this literature, I find in \autoref{unpacking} that \emph{both} elites agreed on imposing the tax on themselves. 








\section{Unpacking the Mechanisms: Chile 1850-1950\label{unpacking}}

% two classes // debate
Historians still debate whether agriculturalists and industrialists comprised two \emph{different} elites. Some claim that this dualism is incorrect.\footnote{See for example  \citet[125]{Mamalakis:1976kx}.} They argue that since landowners also invested in industry,\footnote{\citet[57, 95]{Kirsch:1977aa} who cites \citet[]{Bauer:2008kx}. See also \citet[23]{Coatsworth2002} argue that ``[t]he only landowners that mattered in 19th century Latin American politics were those for whom land represented but one asset in a much broader portfolio.'' In the same vein, \citet[180]{Bauer:2008kx} argues that ``[m]iners and merchants bought haciendas but landowners in turn invested in banks, insurance companies, commercial firms and the incipient industrial sector.''} there was a blurry class division between the mining, banking and agricultural sectors.\footnote{\citet[30, 44, 94, 108]{Bauer:2008kx}.} I contend that there are a series of stylized facts that suggest that there was indeed a structural fracture between the two sectors. Here I explain how there were certain practices that mask the sectoral dualism. For example, it was common that industrialists invested in real state. However, in many instances they did so \emph{just} to obtain credit. \citet[59]{Kirsch:1977aa} explains that ``in a \emph{rural society} land offered one of the best guarantees for loans [since] loans could not be secured by equipment, machinery, or inventory. Only real estate was acceptable collateral.''\footnote{Emphases are mine.} In fact, this practice shows how the credit system was oriented to give unfair advantage to the landed elites. Similarly, \citet[174]{Zeitlin:1984aa} finds that while there were some instances where there were mixed investments, `the combined ownership of capital and landed property was a distinctive quality of \emph{certain} [elites] actors.'\footnote{Emphasis is mine.} There were also other instances where miners invested in banking. However, \citet{Segall1953} argues that Chilean bankers, after the crisis of the mining sector around the 1870s, acquired a number of mineral deposits given as collateral years before, again suggesting that the lack of economic dualism is rather apparent. Similarly, but for the Argentinean case, \citet[609]{Hora2002} explains that `the image of an entrepreneurial elite with assets \emph{scattered throughout several spheres of investment} does not appear entirely correct.'\footnote{Emphasis is mine.} And finally, \citet{Bahamonde:2017aa} explains how the dual \emph{structure} of the economy was \emph{incompatible} with a fully diversified investment portfolio. Concretely, he shows how in some developed Latin American cases the structure of the economy was designed to allocate resources \emph{from} the land \emph{to} the industries, suggesting a situation of sectoral distinctiveness.


% two classes
In all Latin American economies during and right after the colonial period, agriculture was the most important sector.\footnote{\citet[13]{Keller1931}.} And by extension, the economic interests of the agricultural elite were the only economic interests represented in politics.\footnote{\citet[45-46]{Wright1975}.} For example, \citet[106]{Collier:2002db} argue that initially the ``national government was dominated by the central part of the country, with owners of large agricultural holdings playing a predominant role.''\footnote{Similarly, \citet[15]{McBride:1971fv} explains that ``Chile's people live on the soil. Her life is agricultural to the core. \emph{Her government has always been of farm owners. Her Congress is made up chiefly of rich landlords}. Social life is dominated by families whose proudest possession is the ancestral estate.'' Emphases are mine.} Moreover, political institutions and social norms inherited from the colonial period were designed to allocate economic inputs (and hence \emph{growth}) in a way that benefited the landowning class only.\footnote{\citet{Bahamonde:2017aa}.}


% two *antagonist* classes
There existed an important asymmetry. While the industrial sector was growing, they were kept from participating in politics with the same privileges and conditions landowners had. Consequently, it was easy for the agricultural elite to produce policies that were designed to enhance their sector. \citet[13]{Zeitlin:1984aa} argues that ``landowners controlled both the vote and the labor power of the agrarian tenants (\emph{inquilinos}) and dependent peasants (\emph{minifundistas}), and this was the \emph{sine qua non} of their continuing political hegemony.'' In Congress, and the presidency itself, landowners were the single most important group,\footnote{\citet[45]{Bauer:2008kx}.} leaving the modern sector heavily under-represented.\footnote{As \citet[1748]{Baland2008} argue, ``[c]ongressional representation was heavily weighted in favor of rural districts.''} Consequently, fiscal pressures in favor of agricultural taxes were minimal compared with mining taxes,\footnote{As explained, mining was one of the first manifestations of industrial activity. For example,  while an agricultural income tax was imposed, it was weak and abolished after the civil war of 1891.} leaving the agricultural sector systematically  - and substantially - undertaxed relative to other sectors.\footnote{\citet[56]{Best1976}. \citet[81]{Bauer:2008kx} provides a very plausible explanation for why the agricultural sector was ``structurally'' protected against taxation. As he explains, ``[t]he availability of an easily accountable source of public revenue - bags of nitrate or bars of cooper - meant that any need for the Chilean government to intrude into the affairs of landowners was reduced [...] the state kept its political hands off the countryside until the overwhelming urban demands for more food and political support in the 1960s.'' \citet[38]{Zeitlin:1984aa} also points out that ``public revenues came almost exclusively from taxes on mining and its exports.''} Historians explain that ``[i]n those areas where the government did interfere in the countryside, the effect was to strengthen the position of the landowning class.''\footnote{\citet[118]{Bauer:2008kx}.} For example, the little public infrastructure that existed benefited the agricultural sector.\footnote{\citet{Rippy:1971rz,Marichal:1989bh,Zeitlin:1984aa,Bauer:2008kx}.}

% mining and  first and developed industries
For nearly 400 years, mining was the most important activity outside of agriculture. Eventually, the mining sector failed to catch up with more efficient technologies better suited to exploit low-grade ores,\footnote{\citet[53]{Kirsch:1977aa}.} and collapsed. After the mining boom, mining elites shifted their focus to what is considered the first \emph{true} industrial work which began under agricultural auspices: the cotton mills.\footnote{See \citet[231]{Rippy:1971rz}. As \citet[271]{Bethell2008} argues, ``[t]he first power looms were brought [in Per\'u, Ecuador, and Venezuela] in the 1840s, 1850s; but in all three they were a failure, some of the early mills in Ecuador being destroyed by an earthquake. It was not until after 1890 that the textile industries of these nations began to operate with reasonable success. Guatemala's first cotton mill was established in 1882, and between that date and 1910 a few mills appeared in Chile, Argentina, Uruguay, and Colombia.''} The first industries were called \emph{obrajes} and beyond textiles, early industrialists processed other agricultural goods.\footnote{For example, animal grease and tallow, dried and cured meats, flour, bread, beer, wines and spirits, being most of them for domestic consumption (\citet[272]{Bethell2008}). Sugar was used in the production of chocolate, candies and biscuits (\citet[129]{Bertola2012}).} The industrial sector was boosted by favorable international conditions, many times stimulating a positive complementarity between the two sectors. Industrial activities started very small,\footnote{\citet[68]{Marichal:1989bh,Rippy1948}.} progressing ``from the shop to the factory during the latter half of the nineteenth century.''\footnote{\citet[235]{Rippy:1971rz}.} Importantly, modern industrialization did \emph{not} begin with ISI, but around 1900. \citet[129]{Bertola2012} find that the ``fact that manufacturing was alive and thriving in Latin America before the 1929 crash is now beyond question.'' Similarly, \citet[2]{Haber2005} finds that the ``development of large-scale, mechanized (and even ``heavy'') industry can be dated back to the 1890s.''\footnote{For example, \citet{Rippy1948} and \citet{Pfeiffer1952} explain that by the 1870's the carriage industry was on a firm basis.}  



% The Industrial sector and its origins: started very small // class (0)
In Chile, the industrial elite was composed by an incipient, yet strong and cohesive group of individuals. Historian Francisco Encina explains that the members of the non-agricultural class were `not only close associates, or drawn from the same family, but they were the same individuals.'\footnote{In \citet[30]{Zeitlin:1984aa}, emphasis in original. He describes several last names which are still associated with the Chilean elite, such as Ossa, Edwards, Vicu\~{n}a Mackenna, Matta, Goyenechea, Cousi\~{n}o, Urmeneta, Gallo and Subercasaux. Emphasis in the original. Similarly, \citet[48]{Wright1975} supports the thesis that nitrate development led to the development of an ``incipient industrial establishment.''} In the process of going from mineowners to proto-industrialists, this incipient elite developed a strong sense of social \emph{class}.\footnote{\citet[41]{Kirsch:1977aa} explains that the founding of the SOFOFA clearly reflected a ``tension created by the \emph{awareness} of the incongruence between the actual exploitation of economic forces and the potential that could be extracted from them through industrialization,'' emphases are mine.} Sectoral interests were organized as follows. The \emph{Sociedad de Fomento Fabril} (SOFOFA) was founded in 1883 to represent the interests of the the industrial sector against the interests of the agricultural sector, represented by the \emph{Sociedad Nacional de Agricultura} (SNA), founded 45 years earlier. The SNA ``was the most powerful associational interest group in nineteenth-century Chile,''\footnote{\citet[244]{Wright1973}.} and according to \citet[51]{Wright1975}, it clearly thought of itself as a social class. By the 1920s, industrialists started to ``form trade associations to engage in lobbying and propaganda as more coherent interest groups.''\footnote{\citet[107]{Weaver:1980vn}.} 


