% Inter-class inequality and inter-class conflicts // Political bargains
Both economic sectors were similarly developed but only agriculturalists had access to fair political representation. This asymmetry led these two `antagonistic elites'\footnote{\citet[37-38]{Keller1931}.} to confront in the civil wars of 1851-1859 and 1891 between a ``large landed property [elite against a] productive capital [elite].''\footnote{\citet[23]{Zeitlin:1984aa}.} President Balmaceda's overthrowing explains the sectoral nature of these conflicts. On the one hand, he was mainly supported by the landed elites, but later overthrown in 1891 by a mainly industrial/mining coalition.\footnote{\citet[186]{Zeitlin:1984aa}.} While his agenda on ``industrial'' infrastructure (mainly roads and railroads) benefited mostly agricultural areas,\footnote{\citet[124]{Zeitlin:1984aa}.} his attitude towards the banking sector (closely linked to the mining sector)\footnote{\citet[118]{Zeitlin:1984aa}.} was `all but confiscatory.'\footnote{\citet[175]{Zeitlin:1984aa}.} On the other hand, however, he failed to secure a coalition with his own sector. \citet[127]{Zeitlin:1984aa} explains that the `decline of wheat exports [...] came precisely when a vast new market for agriculture was growing in the nitrate territory.' As the agricultural sector supplied the industrial areas with foodstuff, it simultaneously increased the \emph{sectoral dependence} of the agricultural elites on the industrial sector, forcing the ``landed proprietors [to] become dependent to a considerable extent on the continuing prosperity of the major nitrate capitalists.''\footnote{\citet[129]{Zeitlin:1984aa}.} He explains that while biased investments against the industrial class played an important role, the sectoral economic dependence between the two sectors was the major factor that mobilized both elites into the civil war of 1891. Ultimately, this case illustrates the sectoral economic conflicts between the two elites. While it would be inaccurate to say that Balmaceda was \emph{completely} supported by agriculturalists and \emph{completely} opposed by industrialists, this example illustrates how (failed) inter-sectoral alliances and biased public goods provision against industrialists led these two groups to a military conflict in 1891. Lower levels of inter-elite inequality gave both elites access to military resources. While \emph{Balmacedistas} managed to secure support with of army, \emph{congresistas} (the anti-Balmaceda group) managed to gather support of the navy. 

The conflict left a permanent scar in the Chilean society. While the civil war lasted only nine months, it took 10,000 lives (out of a total population of 3 million people) and cost more than \$ 100 million,\footnote{\citet[86]{Zeitlin:1984aa}.} a significant amount for a small country. This legacy materialized in an inefficient but politically stable political system for several years. In part, the immobilism was due to the fact that the political reforms that gave way to a `parliamentary' system came from the conflicting elites themselves.\footnote{\citet[108]{Collier:2002db}.} However, the intention to avoid more violence (at least among the elites) tended to persist. For instance, while all ``ministers, counselors of state, members of the constituent congress [,] municipal officials, provincial governors and intendants, members of the judiciary and even the lowest functionaries and ordinary employees of Balmaceda's government were investigated [or] brought to trial,''\footnote{\citet[87]{Zeitlin:1984aa}.} there were a number of amnesties issued. Similarly, there were a number of \emph{aborted} coups in 1907, 1912, 1915 and 1919.\footnote{\citet[109]{Collier:2002db}.} I identify a third additional factor. War was more likely to exhaust all existent assets without producing positive outcomes for either sector, putting pressures for a sectoral compromise.\footnote{Similarly, \citet{Geddes1991} argues that competition between two rival parties of about the same size creates clearer incentives to invest in political institutions.} Three institutional components were considered: an income tax, industrial protectionism, and equal access to the state. Here I focus on the first component.\footnote{The SOFOFA pursued a very strong protectionist agenda. \citet[122]{Sokoloff2007a} explain that the expansion of ``manufacturing production [...] helped to nurture the development of a powerful constituency for higher tariffs.'' In fact, \citet[53]{Lederman2005} finds that in Chile the timing of protectionist and income taxation cycles matches, suggesting the plausibility of the sectoral bargains that took place around in the 1920's between the two elites. See for a similar view \citet[18]{Haber2005}.} The faster the industrial growth, the higher the pressures to impose a tax to capture increasing industrial incomes. This is in line with  \citet[59]{Besley:2011aa} who argue that ``investing in fiscal capacity becomes more attractive [...] when wages or incomes [...] are higher.''\footnote{Similarly, see \citet[647]{Campbell1994} who explain that ``economic development should be directly related to individual and corporate income tax rates.''} \citet{Beramendi2016} also find that investments in fiscal capacities are conditional on the expansion of the industrial sector.



The income tax law was passed in Chile in the middle of big political instability. In 1920 President Alessandri obtained a very close victory against Luis Barros Borgo\~no,\footnote{\citet[111]{Collier:1999rz}.} who was supported by `the dominant political and landed aristocracy.'\footnote{\citet[2]{Haring1931}.} Governability was seriously compromised as the election let the senate in control of the landowning class, who roundly opposed tax reforms.\footnote{\citet[5]{Haring1931}.} Particularly, the opposition had `serious differences [...] over [Alessandri's] legislative program, eespecially in connection with the proposed income tax.'\footnote{\citet[3]{Haring1931}.} Eventually, in 1924 the income tax law was passed. As others explain, the non-agricultural ``accepted taxation, \emph{while demanding state services and expecting to influence how tax revenues were spent}.''\footnote{Carmenza Gallo, in \citet[165]{Brautigam2008}. Emphases are mine. She refers specifically to the mining elites.} The law taxed 2\% on professional income above 2,400 pesos, 3.5\% on net profits in industry and  commerce above the same sum, 5\% on income from mining, and 9\% per cent on incomes from real estate.\footnote{\citet[552]{James1924}.} Humud (1969, p. 154) explains that the income tax generated considerable resources, and that the tax in ``1930 [it] would become second only to import duties in size.''\footnote{\citet[451-452]{Bowman1982}.} In turn, the military was concerned with the general budget situation. Salaries of army and navy officers `were two months in arrears.'\footnote{\citet[6]{Haring1931}.} Famously, on September 3 of 1924 young officials attend the galleries of the senate and made noise with their sabers to demonstrate their discontent. After the resignation of the entire cabinet, president Alessandri sided with the army in an effort to accelerate the implementation of several pieces of legislation that have been blocked by congress for months. 


\todo{check paragraph below: include my papers, and last paragraph from EQ paper.}

The implementation of the income tax in Chile was associated with the implementation of other state institutions, expanding the bureaucratic \emph{dominion} of the state. However, unlike other `regular' state institutions and services, taxing incomes in fact infiltrated the state's coercive sovereignty unto the individual itself. It was the practice of this technology that gave the state the big push allowing the reproduction of its power in other areas throughout the territory. Following the fiscal sociology paradigm, I contend that the more effectively the state taxed its subjects, the more knowledge accumulated performing \emph{other} state activities. The knowledge and expertise the state accumulated were transfered to other state institutions via spillovers, augmenting the overall levels of \emph{stateness}. For instance, it was necessary to send official emissaries to check on accounting books of the refinery in the north, the winery in the central valley and the \emph{hacienda} in the south. Eventually, these delegations became more complex, increasing the density of state presence in the territory. For instance, \citet{Strayer:2005uq} explains how official state delegations traveled the territory dispensing judicial decisions, fostering state centralization. \citet{Besley2013a} explain that implementing the income tax law is ``associated with investments in public administrative structures that support tax collection.'' For instance \citet{Bahamonde:2017ac} finds that fiscal effectiveness can be explained in that (1) elites carried a big chunk of the burden, and that (2) the most influential economic groups agreed on the implementation of the tax.\footnote{See also \citet{Beramendi2016}.} In fact, \citet{Bergman2003} explains that Chile is one of the few successful cases of tax compliance in Latin America. 




