\section{Econometric Analyses\label{methods}}

% Operationalization, case selection, and data
Following the economic development typology suggested in \citet[5]{Mahoney:2010aa}, nine polities were selected. Three `higher level' countries (Argentina, Chile and Venezuela), three `intermediate level' countries (Mexico, Colombia and Per\'u), and three `lower level' countries (Ecuador, Nicaragua and Guatemala). I proxy sectoral conflicts and specifically the degree in which the industrial elites challenged incumbent landowners by using industrial and agricultural sectoral growth rates as presented in the  \href{http://moxlad-staging.herokuapp.com/home/en?}{MOxLAD} data.\footnote{``These data build on the studies and statistical abstracts of the Economic Commission for Latin America, but also rely on Mitchell's International Historical Statistics, International Monetary Fund's International Financial Statistics, the World Bank's World Development Indicators and a variety of national sources.'' I used the \emph{agriculture value-added} and \emph{manufacturing value-added} variables. The former measures ``the output of the sector net of intermediate inputs and includes the cultivation of crops, livestock production, hunting, forestry and fishing.'' The later  ``[r]eports the output of the sector net of intermediate inputs.'' Both of them are expressed in local currency at 1970 constant prices.} The dataset spans from 1900 to (potentially) 2010.\footnote{As I explain later, I test this argument within the duration model approach. Since countries are censored once they implement the income tax law, they leave the sample potentially before 2010.} According to \citet[790]{Astorga2005}, these data provide extended comparable sectoral value-added series in constant purchasing power parity prices.\footnote{Using a similar strategy, \citet[]{Thies2005a} also uses data on taxation and compare those data between cross sections.} Using secondary information, \autoref{sample:data:income:tax:tab} states \emph{when} the income tax was implemented, which was the specific law, and its corresponding source(s). \autoref{fig:incometax} shows both sectoral outputs (independent variables) and the year when the income tax law was passed (dependent variable). Since population has been associated with the probability elites expand the franchise,\footnote{\citet[892-893]{Engerman2005}.} and consequently the tax base, I include total country-year population as a control variable.


